 31s OATHTOOL(1)                           User Commands                          OATHTOOL(1)
 31s 
 31s NAME
 31s        oathtool - Open AuTHentication (OATH) one-time password tool
 31s 
 31s SYNOPSIS
 31s        oathtool [OPTION]... [KEY [OTP]]...
 31s 
 31s DESCRIPTION
 31s        Generate  and validate OATH one-time passwords.  KEY and OTP is the string '-' to
 31s        read from standard input, '@FILE' to read from indicated filename, or a  hex  en‐
 31s        coded value (not recommended on multi-user systems).
 31s 
 31s        -h, --help
 31s               Print help and exit
 31s 
 31s        -V, --version
 31s               Print version and exit
 31s 
 31s        --hotp use event-based HOTP mode  (default=on)
 31s 
 31s        --totp[=MODE]
 31s               use  time-variant  TOTP  mode (values "SHA1", "SHA256", or "SHA512")  (de‐
 31s               fault=`SHA1')
 31s 
 31s        -b, --base32
 31s               use base32 encoding of KEY instead of hex (default=off)
 31s 
 31s        -c, --counter=COUNTER
 31s               HOTP counter value
 31s 
 31s        -s, --time-step-size=DURATION TOTP time-step duration
 31s               (default=`30s')
 31s 
 31s        -S, --start-time=TIME
 31s               when to start counting time steps for TOTP  (default=`1970-01-01  00:00:00
 31s               UTC')
 31s 
 31s        -N, --now=TIME
 31s               use this time as current time for TOTP (default=`now')
 31s 
 31s        -d, --digits=DIGITS
 31s               number of digits in one-time password
 31s 
 31s        -w, --window=WIDTH
 31s               number of additional OTPs to generate or validate against
 31s 
 31s        -v, --verbose
 31s               explain what is being done  (default=off)
 31s 
 31s EXAMPLES
 31s        To generate a time-based (TOTP) one-time password from a key protected by GnuPG:
 31s 
 31s          $ gpg --decrypt --quiet ~/.my-totp-secret.asc | oathtool --totp -
 31s 
 31s        How  to create the encrypted file is outside of scope of this manual, see gpg(1),
 31s        however the following two commands may help you to encrypt the  secret  symmetri‐
 31s        cally  (using  a password) or asymmetrically (if you have created a private key),
 31s        respectively.  You will need to provide the secret from the terminal after invok‐
 31s        ing the commands.
 31s 
 31s          $ gpg --symmetric > ~/.my-totp-secret.asc
 31s          $ gpg --encrypt --default-recipient-self > ~/.my-totp-secret.asc
 31s 
 31s        For  easier  reading,  the  rest of this man page provides the KEY and OTP on the
 31s        command line.  Keep in mind that this usage is  not  recommended  since  on  most
 31s        multi-user  systems,  command-line parameters of running processes can be seen by
 31s        other users.
 31s 
 31s        To generate the first event-based (HOTP) one-time password for an all-zero key:
 31s 
 31s           $ echo 00 | oathtool -
 31s           328482
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        Sometime you want to generate more than a single OTP.  To generate 10  additional
 31s        event-based  one-time  passwords, with the secret key used in the examples of RFC
 31s        4226, use the -w (--window) parameter:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool -w 10 3132333435363738393031323334353637383930
 31s           755224
 31s           287082
 31s           359152
 31s           969429
 31s           338314
 31s           254676
 31s           287922
 31s           162583
 31s           399871
 31s           520489
 31s           403154
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        In the last output, the counter for the first OTP was 0, the  second  OTP  had  a
 31s        counter of 1, and so on up to 10.
 31s 
 31s        In  order  to  use  keys encoded in Base32 instead of hex, you may provide the -b
 31s        (--base32) parameter:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --base32 -w 3 GEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQGEZDGNBVGY3TQOJQ
 31s           755224
 31s           287082
 31s           359152
 31s           969429
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        The tool ignore whitespace in base32 data and re-add padding if  necessary,  thus
 31s        you may supply keys formatted like the one below.
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --base32 --totp "gr6d 5br7 25s6 vnck v4vl hlao re"
 31s           977872
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        To  generate a particular OTP, use the -c (--counter) parameter to give the exact
 31s        position directly:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool -c 5 3132333435363738393031323334353637383930
 31s           254676
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        To validate a HOTP one-time password supply the OTP last on the command line:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool -w 10 3132333435363738393031323334353637383930 969429
 31s           3
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        The output indicates the counter that  was  used.   It  works  by  starting  with
 31s        counter  0  and  increment  until it founds a match (or not), within the supplied
 31s        window of 10 OTPs.
 31s 
 31s        The tool supports time-variant one-time passwords, in so called TOTP mode.  Usage
 31s        is similar, but --totp needs to be provided:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --totp 00
 31s           943388
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        Don't  be  alarmed  if you do not get the same output, this is because the output
 31s        depends on the current time.  To generate a TOTP for a particular fixed time  use
 31s        the -N (--now) parameter:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --totp --now "2008-04-23 17:42:17 UTC" 00
 31s           974945
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        The  format  is  a mostly free format human readable date string such as "Sun, 29
 31s        Feb 2004 16:21:42 -0800" or "2004-02-29 16:21:42" or even "next Thursday".  It is
 31s        the same used as the --date parameter of the date(1) tool.
 31s 
 31s        The  default MAC algorithm to use with TOTP is HMAC-SHA1 and this is what is usu‐
 31s        ally used.  The  tool  supports  two  other  MACs,  namely  the  HMAC-SHA256  and
 31s        HMAC-SHA512 as well.  To use either of these, qualify the --totp parameter with a
 31s        value.  Use "SHA256" for HMAC-SHA256 and "SHA512" for HMAC-SHA512.  The following
 31s        demonstrate generating one of the RFC 6238 test vectors.
 31s 
 31s           $   oathtool   --totp=SHA256   --digits=8   --now  "2009-02-13  23:31:30  UTC"
 31s        3132333435363738393031323334353637383930313233343536373839303132
 31s           91819424
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        You may generate several TOTPs by specifying the --window parameter,  similar  to
 31s        how  it  works  for  HOTP.   The OTPs generated here will be for the initial time
 31s        (normally current time) and then each following time step (e.g., 30  second  win‐
 31s        dow).
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --totp 00 -w5
 31s           815120
 31s           003818
 31s           814756
 31s           184042
 31s           582326
 31s           733842
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        You  can  validate  a TOTP one-time password by supplying the secret and a window
 31s        parameter (number of time steps before or after current time):
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --totp -w 5 00 `oathtool --totp 00`
 31s           0
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        Similar when generating TOTPs, you can use a -N (--now) parameter to specify  the
 31s        time to use instead of the current time:
 31s 
 31s          $    oathtool    --totp    --now="2005-03-18    01:58:29   UTC"   -w   10000000
 31s        3132333435363738393031323334353637383930 89005924
 31s          4115227
 31s          $
 31s 
 31s        The previous test uses values from the TOTP specification and  will  stress  test
 31s        the tool because the expected window is around 4 million time-steps.
 31s 
 31s        There are two system parameters for TOTP: the time-step size and the time start.
 31s 
 31s        By  default the time-step size is 30 seconds, which means you get a new OTP every
 31s        30 seconds.  You may modify this with the -s (--time-step-size) parameter:
 31s 
 31s           $ oathtool --totp --time-step-size=45s 00
 31s           109841
 31s           $
 31s 
 31s        The       values       are       valid       ISO-8601       durations,       see:
